      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nBoth of these results make excellent chemical sense:\n\n- **DTPA** is an octadentate chelator with five carboxylate groups and three tertiary amine nitrogens, giving it up to 8 dissociable protons (5 from –COOH groups and 3 from –NH⁺– sites). It is widely used in MRI contrast agents (e.g., Gd-DTPA) and nuclear medicine.\n\n- **NTP (Nitrilotris(methylenephosphonic acid))** contains three phosphonate groups (–PO₃H₂) plus a central nitrogen, providing up to 7 protonation steps. Phosphonates are industrially important as scale inhibitors and corrosion preventers.\n\nThese polyprotic ligands are among the most complex acid-base systems catalogued in the database, reflecting their rich stepwise protonation chemistry.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes)*",
